      "content": "Now I have enough to diagnose the issue. Let me trace through the desugaring of the specific `match` expression to understand the IR that gets produced:\n\nThe expression is:\n```menai\n(lambda (c) (match c ((? string? s) #t) (_ #f)))\n```\n\nThe `match` desugars to (roughly):\n```menai\n(let ((#:match-tmp-1 c))\n  (if (string? #:match-tmp-1)\n      (let ((s #:match-tmp-1))\n        #t)\n      #f))\n```\n\nAfter copy propagation and dead-code elimination, `s` is dead (it's never used in `#t`), and the let binding for `#:match-tmp-1` is also copyable. So the IR simplifies to:\n\n```menai\n(if (string? c) #t #f)\n```\n\nAnd **this is exactly where the `(if cond #t #f) \u2192 cond` rule in `_opt_if` should fire!** Let me look more carefully at what's happening. The issue is the ordering of the passes \u2014 copy propagation runs first, then `MenaiIROptimizer`. But `MenaiIROptimizer._opt_if` does check for `(if cond #t #f) \u2192 cond`. So why doesn't it fire?\n\nThe key clue is in the bytecode \u2014 we see `LOAD_TRUE` and `LOAD_FALSE` as separate instructions, not just `STRING_P`. This means the `(if cond #t #f) \u2192 cond` optimization is **not** being applied. Let me check whether the `MenaiIRIf` node's `in_tail_position` flag or the structure of the IR after desugaring might be interfering. Let me look at the IR builder to understand the structure:",
