      "content": "Now I can see the full picture. Let me focus on the critical detail \u2014 when `_analyze_if` runs in tail position, it wraps both branches in `MenaiIRReturn`:\n\n```python\nif in_tail_position:\n    if self._needs_return_wrapper(then_plan):\n        then_plan = MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=then_plan)\n    if self._needs_return_wrapper(else_plan):\n        else_plan = MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=else_plan)\n```\n\nSo after desugaring and IR building, the inner `(if (string? c) #t #f)` \u2014 which IS in tail position inside the lambda \u2014 becomes:\n\n```\nMenaiIRIf(\n    condition=MenaiIRCall(string?),\n    then=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t)),\n    else=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#f)),\n    in_tail_position=True\n)\n```\n\nNow look at `_opt_if` in the optimizer \u2014 the boolean identity check:\n\n```python\nif (isinstance(opt_then, MenaiIRConstant) and isinstance(opt_then.value, MenaiBoolean) ...\n```\n\n**The `then_plan` and `else_plan` are NOT `MenaiIRConstant` nodes \u2014 they are `MenaiIRReturn` nodes wrapping `MenaiIRConstant` nodes.** The optimizer checks `opt_then` directly against `MenaiIRConstant`, but `opt_then` is actually `MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t))`. The pattern doesn't match, so the optimization is skipped.",
