      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Now I have the complete picture. Let me look at the existing unit tests for the boolean identity optimization \u2014 they test the `(if cond #t #f)` pattern but only with `MenaiIRConstant` branches directly inside the `MenaiIRIf`, **not** with `MenaiIRReturn`-wrapped branches, which is what actually appears in tail position. This confirms the diagnosis.\n\nHere's the root cause, clearly explained:\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe bug is in `MenaiIROptimizer._opt_if`. The boolean identity elimination check is:\n\n```python\nif (isinstance(opt_then, MenaiIRConstant)\n        and isinstance(opt_then.value, MenaiBoolean)\n        and isinstance(opt_else, MenaiIRConstant)\n        and isinstance(opt_else.value, MenaiBoolean)):\n```\n\nThis checks that `opt_then` and `opt_else` are **directly** `MenaiIRConstant` nodes. But the IR builder, in `_analyze_if`, wraps both branches in `MenaiIRReturn` when the `if` is in tail position:\n\n```python\nif in_tail_position:\n    if self._needs_return_wrapper(then_plan):\n        then_plan = MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=then_plan)\n    if self._needs_return_wrapper(else_plan):\n        else_plan = MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=else_plan)\n```\n\nSo for `(lambda (c) (match c ((? string? s) #t) (_ #f)))`, after desugaring and copy propagation the inner `if` is in tail position and its branches become:\n\n```\nMenaiIRIf(\n    condition=MenaiIRCall(string?),\n    then=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t)),   \u2190 not a bare MenaiIRConstant\n    else=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#f)),   \u2190 not a bare MenaiIRConstant\n    in_tail_position=True\n)\n```\n\nThe optimizer's `isinstance(opt_then, MenaiIRConstant)` check fails because `opt_then` is `MenaiIRReturn(...)`, not `MenaiIRConstant(...)`. The optimization is never applied, and the compiler falls back to the full `JUMP_IF_TRUE`/`LOAD_TRUE`/`LOAD_FALSE` sequence instead of the single `STRING_P` result.\n\nThe fix needs to look *through* a `MenaiIRReturn` wrapper when checking for the boolean identity pattern, and if it fires, return the condition directly (for the `#t/#f` case) or a `boolean-not` call (for the `#f/#t` case) \u2014 also wrapped in a `MenaiIRReturn` since we're in tail position.\n\nLet me now implement the fix:",
