      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Now I see the issue. When `MenaiIRInlineOnce` inlines a single-use binding, the `_substitute` method replaces a `MenaiIRVariable` with the value that was bound. When the inlined value is a `MenaiIRConstant` (like `#t` or `#f`), it gets substituted directly at the use site \u2014 which might be inside a `MenaiIRReturn` node. So after inlining, the `MenaiIRIf` branches could look like:\n\n- `then_plan = MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRVariable(s))` \u2192 after substituting `s = MenaiIRConstant(#t)` \u2192 `MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t))` \u2713 still wrapped\n\nBut wait \u2014 the `_inline_let` can also eliminate the `let` entirely and return just the body. And the body might be an `MenaiIRIf` where branches were originally wrapped by the IR builder...\n\nActually, the key scenario is: what if the `MenaiIRIf` is **not** in tail position (e.g., it's the condition of another `if`)? Then the IR builder does NOT wrap its branches. So we'd have:\n\n```\nMenaiIRIf(\n    condition=MenaiIRCall(string?),\n    then=MenaiIRConstant(#t),   \u2190 unwrapped (not in tail position)\n    else=MenaiIRConstant(#f),   \u2190 unwrapped\n    in_tail_position=False\n)\n```\n\n`then_wrapped=False, else_wrapped=False` \u2192 assertion passes, optimization fires correctly, returns `MenaiIRCall(string?)` (bare, no wrapper). \u2713\n\nAnd for tail-position:\n```\nMenaiIRIf(\n    condition=MenaiIRCall(string?),\n    then=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t)),   \u2190 wrapped\n    else=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#f)),   \u2190 wrapped\n    in_tail_position=True\n)\n```\n`then_wrapped=True, else_wrapped=True` \u2192 assertion passes, returns `MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRCall(string?))`. \u2713\n\nSo when would `then_wrapped != else_wrapped`? Let me think... After the constant-condition elimination fires and returns `opt_then` (which is `MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t))`), the outer context receives a `MenaiIRReturn`. Then on the next optimizer pass, the `MenaiIRReturn` handler calls `self._opt(ir.value_plan, frame_stack)` on `MenaiIRConstant(#t)`, which just returns it unchanged. So no asymmetry there.\n\nWhat about the `test_nested_identity_forms` test? The inner `(if (boolean? x) #t #f)` is used as the condition of the outer `if`. So the inner `if` is in non-tail position \u2192 branches unwrapped. The outer `if` is in tail position inside the lambda \u2192 branches wrapped with `MenaiIRReturn`. After the optimizer processes the inner `if` (constant identity \u2192 returns bare `MenaiIRCall(boolean?)`), the outer `if` still has wrapped branches. No asymmetry.\n\nLet me look at what's actually happening by checking the full error output more carefully. The `FAILED` tests are the simple integration ones like `test_identity_form_true_input`. Let me re-read:\n\n```\nFAILED tests/menai/test_ir_optimizer_boolean_identity.py::TestBooleanIdentityIntegration::test_identity_form_true_input\n```\n\nThis compiles `(if (boolean? #t) #t #f)`. After constant folding, `(boolean? #t)` \u2192 `#t`. So the expression becomes `(if #t #t #f)`. At the top level, `in_tail_position=True`. The IR builder produces:\n\n```\nMenaiIRIf(\n    condition=MenaiIRConstant(#t),\n    then=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t)),\n    else=MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#f)),\n    in_tail_position=True\n)\n```\n\nThe optimizer's constant-condition elimination fires first: `opt_condition=MenaiIRConstant(#t)` \u2192 returns `opt_then = MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t))`. This is correct and the assertion is never reached for this test. So why is it FAILED?\n\nThe FAILED tests are different from the ERROR tests. Let me re-read the output:\n- `FAILED` = test ran but assertion failed\n- `ERROR` = test raised an unexpected exception (our `AssertionError`)\n\nThe `FAILED` tests (`test_identity_form_true_input` etc.) are failing because... the optimization is now working and changing the result? No \u2014 they were passing before. Let me re-read the output more carefully. The `AssertionError` is in the `ERROR` tests (inside lambdas). The `FAILED` tests might be failing for a different reason.\n\nActually, wait \u2014 the `FAILED` ones could be failing because the `AssertionError` in another test is contaminating the test session, or because the optimization is producing wrong results. Let me run the tests with more detail:",
