      "id": "a1976d0d-2d42-42b8-b984-726b79682d5e",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:25:07.708865+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Now I can see it clearly. Look at the prelude at line 56-60:\n\n```menai\n(if ($list-null? lst)\n    #t                          \u2190 tail position, wrapped: MenaiIRReturn(#t)\n    (if ($boolean=? prev ...)\n        (loop ...)              \u2190 tail call, NOT wrapped (is_tail_call=True)\n        #f))                    \u2190 tail position, wrapped: MenaiIRReturn(#f)\n```\n\nThe inner `if ($boolean=? prev ... ) (loop ...) #f` has:\n- `then = MenaiIRCall(loop, is_tail_call=True)` \u2014 **not** wrapped (tail calls don't need `MenaiIRReturn`)\n- `else = MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#f))` \u2014 **wrapped**\n\nThat's the legitimate asymmetry. The IR builder wraps based on `_needs_return_wrapper`, and tail calls return `False` from that function. This is a valid, permanent structural feature of the IR, not a bug in any transformation pass.\n\nSo the assertion is simply wrong \u2014 asymmetric wrapping is a normal, correct state. The fix needs to be: look through `MenaiIRReturn` wrappers when checking for the boolean identity pattern, and **use `ir.in_tail_position`** (the original flag on the `MenaiIRIf`) to decide whether to wrap the result, rather than inferring it from the branches.",
