      "id": "490d9087-10e3-4a28-a7b0-971a67df17e6",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:26:33.213502+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Good progress \u2014 the integration tests all pass now. The 3 remaining failures are unit tests that construct `MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=MenaiIRIf(..., in_tail_position=True, then=bare_const, else=bare_const))`. With `in_tail_position=True` we now wrap the result in `MenaiIRReturn`, but the outer `MenaiIRReturn` is already there, giving a double-wrap.\n\nThe unit tests construct the IR with the `MenaiIRIf` already inside a `MenaiIRReturn`, with **bare** (unwrapped) branch constants. That's the non-tail-position-wrapped style \u2014 but `in_tail_position=True`. This is the inconsistency in the unit tests themselves: they set `in_tail_position=True` on the `MenaiIRIf` but don't wrap the branches, which is not what the IR builder actually produces.\n\nThe right signal is indeed the branch-wrapping state \u2014 specifically whether the branches that *are* constants have been wrapped. Let me look at the error message more carefully: the result is `MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=MenaiIRReturn(...))` \u2014 a double wrap. The outer `MenaiIRReturn` comes from the `_opt` handler for `MenaiIRReturn` (line 86), and the inner one from our new code. So the unit test structure is:\n\n```\nMenaiIRReturn(          \u2190 outer, from test setup\n  MenaiIRIf(\n    in_tail_position=True,\n    then=MenaiIRConstant(#f),   \u2190 bare, no inner Return\n    else=MenaiIRConstant(#t),   \u2190 bare, no inner Return\n  )\n)\n```\n\nWhen `_opt` processes the outer `MenaiIRReturn`, it calls `_opt` on the `MenaiIRIf`. Our code sees `in_tail_position=True` and wraps the result in another `MenaiIRReturn`. That's wrong for this case.\n\nThe real IR builder **never** produces a bare-constant branch inside an `in_tail_position=True` if \u2014 it always wraps them. So `in_tail_position=True` with bare branches is an inconsistent state that only the unit tests produce. The correct signal is: **wrap the result iff the constant branches themselves were wrapped**. And for the asymmetric case (one tail-call branch, one constant branch), we only care about the constant branch's wrapping state.\n\nSo the right logic is: check if either of the two **constant** branches is wrapped, and use that to decide. Since both constants should be consistently wrapped (both wrapped or both bare \u2014 it's the non-constant branches like tail calls that can be asymmetric), we can just check `then_inner` vs `then` (i.e., `then_wrapped`).",
      "completed": true,
      "usage": {
        "prompt_tokens": 108946,
        "completion_tokens": 1444,
        "total_tokens": 110390
      },
      "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
      "reasoning_capability": 1,
      "temperature": 0.7,
      "tool_calls": [
        {
          "id": "toolu_01FcdtcrwuyNkoyiuoH8o14b",
          "name": "editor",
          "arguments": {
            "operation": "apply_diff",
            "tab_id": "10e2214e-9c38-482d-b9dd-fac03941eebb",
            "diff_content": "@@ -174,9 +174,11 @@\n         # The IR builder wraps tail-position branches in MenaiIRReturn.  Branches\n         # can be asymmetrically wrapped (e.g. one is a tail call that needs no\n         # wrapper, the other is a constant that does), so we use in_tail_position\n-        # to decide whether the replacement needs wrapping, and look through any\n-        # existing wrapper just to reach the inner constant for the pattern check.\n-        then_inner, _ = self._unwrap_return(opt_then)\n-        else_inner, _ = self._unwrap_return(opt_else)\n+        # to decide whether the replacement needs wrapping.  We look through any\n+        # MenaiIRReturn wrapper on each branch to reach the inner constant.  When\n+        # both branches are boolean constants, they are always symmetrically\n+        # wrapped (both wrapped or both bare), so then_wrapped is the right signal.\n+        then_inner, then_wrapped = self._unwrap_return(opt_then)\n+        else_inner, _ = self._unwrap_return(opt_else)\n         if (isinstance(then_inner, MenaiIRConstant)\n                 and isinstance(then_inner.value, MenaiBoolean)\n                 and isinstance(else_inner, MenaiIRConstant)\n@@ -185,13 +187,13 @@\n             if then_inner.value.value and not else_inner.value.value:\n                 # (if cond #t #f) \u2192  cond  (or Return(cond) in tail position)\n                 self._eliminations += 1\n-                if ir.in_tail_position:\n+                if then_wrapped:\n                     return MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=opt_condition)\n                 return opt_condition\n \n             if not then_inner.value.value and else_inner.value.value:\n                 # (if cond #f #t) \u2192 (boolean-not cond)\n                 self._eliminations += 1\n                 not_call = MenaiIRCall(\n                     func_plan=MenaiIRVariable(\n                             name='boolean-not', var_type='global'\n                     ),\n                     arg_plans=[opt_condition],\n                     is_tail_call=ir.in_tail_position,\n                     is_builtin=True,\n                     builtin_name='boolean-not',\n                 )\n-                if ir.in_tail_position:\n+                if then_wrapped:\n                     return MenaiIRReturn(value_plan=not_call)\n                 return not_call\n"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
