    {
      "id": "53366df1-030b-4946-9bd0-18117943e80f",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:29:36.716815+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Found it. The test cases are `(and \"hello\" #t)` and `(or 1 #f)`. These desugar to:\n\n- `(and \"hello\" #t)` \u2192 `(if \"hello\" #t #f)` \u2014 condition is `\"hello\"` (a string), branches are `#t` and `#f`\n- `(or 1 #f)` \u2192 `(if 1 #t #f)` \u2014 condition is `1` (an integer), branches are `#t` and `#f`\n\nOur optimization now fires on `(if <anything> #t #f)` and replaces it with `<anything>` directly \u2014 bypassing the runtime type check on the condition that `JUMP_IF_TRUE/FALSE` would perform. This is semantically wrong: the optimization is only valid when the condition is **known to be boolean** (i.e., it's the result of a predicate call or another boolean expression).\n\nThe fix is straightforward: the `(if cond #t #f) \u2192 cond` rewrite is only sound when `cond` is guaranteed to produce a boolean. We need to check that `opt_condition` is a call to a known boolean-returning builtin (a predicate), or is itself a boolean constant or another boolean-producing expression.\n\nThe simplest safe criterion: only apply the optimization when `opt_condition` is a builtin call whose `builtin_name` ends in `?` (a predicate), or is a `MenaiIRConstant` of boolean type, or is another `MenaiIRCall` with `builtin_name='boolean-not'`.",
