    {
      "id": "61748c30-66f1-4b32-9685-c710b531404f",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:30:52.912638+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "Clean and correct. Here's a full summary of what was found and fixed:\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n### Root cause \u2014 three separate issues, all in `_opt_if`\n\n**1. The `MenaiIRReturn` wrapper blindspot (the original bug)**\n\nThe IR builder wraps both branches of a tail-position `if` in `MenaiIRReturn`. So inside a lambda, `(if (string? c) #t #f)` produces:\n\n```\nMenaiIRIf(\n    condition = MenaiIRCall(string?),\n    then      = MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t)),   \u2190 wrapped\n    else      = MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#f)),   \u2190 wrapped\n    in_tail_position = True\n)\n```\n\nThe old `_opt_if` checked `isinstance(opt_then, MenaiIRConstant)` \u2014 which fails because `opt_then` is a `MenaiIRReturn`, not a bare constant. The fix: `_unwrap_return()` peeks through the wrapper to reach the inner constant for the pattern check.\n\n**2. Asymmetric branch wrapping**\n\nA branch is only wrapped in `MenaiIRReturn` when `_needs_return_wrapper()` returns `True`. Tail calls return `False` from that function, so a legitimate IR can have one branch wrapped and the other not (e.g. `then = MenaiIRReturn(MenaiIRConstant(#t))`, `else = MenaiIRCall(loop, is_tail_call=True)`). The wrapping state of the constant branches is the right signal for whether to re-wrap the replacement \u2014 not `in_tail_position`, which doesn't account for this, and not an assertion that both sides are symmetric.\n\n**3. Missing boolean-type guard (the soundness bug)**\n\n`(if cond #t #f) \u2192 cond` is only semantically valid when `cond` is guaranteed to produce a boolean. The VM's `JUMP_IF_TRUE/FALSE` opcodes enforce this at runtime \u2014 replacing the `if` with `cond` directly bypasses that check. `(and \"hello\" #t)` desugars to `(if \"hello\" #t #f)`, which must still raise a type error at runtime. The fix: `_is_boolean_typed()` conservatively approves only boolean constants, predicate calls (builtins ending in `?`), and `boolean-not` calls.",
