      "temperature": 0.7
    },
    {
      "id": "216c9f0d-b53f-4e83-8b8d-4552c80b4bcb",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:49:37.590004+00:00",
      "type": "user_message",
      "content": "your new method `_is_boolean_typed` seems to be very conservative about checking predicates or `boolean_not`. Why can't this be any function that returns a boolean?",
      "completed": true,
      "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
      "reasoning_capability": 1,
      "temperature": 0.7
    },
    {
      "id": "e869aba3-6b10-4b94-9294-21833d4e90a0",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:49:40.914629+00:00",
      "type": "ai_connected",
      "content": "AI is thinking...",
      "completed": true,
      "model": "claude-sonnet-4-6",
      "reasoning_capability": 1,
      "temperature": 0.7
    },
    {
      "id": "8f278a5b-e4b5-4d35-9a9a-437068782da1",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-08T11:49:40.927263+00:00",
      "type": "ai_response",
      "content": "You're right \u2014 it's overly conservative. Any expression that's known to return a boolean is a valid candidate. The existing `_opt_if` already handles `(if #t ...)` and `(if #f ...)` via constant-condition elimination, so the only remaining cases to consider are:\n\n- Any builtin call whose result is always boolean \u2014 that's predicates (`?`-suffixed) and `boolean-not`, which is what we have now\n- A nested `MenaiIRIf` that is itself in boolean-identity-eliminated form (i.e. it's already been reduced to returning a boolean)\n- Any user-defined function call \u2014 but we can't know the return type of those\n\nThe real gap is the nested `MenaiIRIf` case, but more importantly: we're already inside the optimizer's fixed-point loop. If a nested `if` gets reduced to a predicate call on one pass, the next pass will catch the outer `if`. So the only thing `_is_boolean_typed` genuinely needs to handle is what can appear as a condition *after all passes have run* \u2014 and that's exactly predicate calls and `boolean-not`.\n\nActually, let me think harder. What about a user function that wraps a predicate?\n\n```menai\n(let ((my-pred (lambda (x) (string? x))))\n  (if (my-pred c) #t #f))\n```\n\nAfter `MenaiIRInlineOnce` inlines `my-pred`, the condition becomes `MenaiIRCall(string?)` \u2014 a predicate, caught by the current check. But if it's called more than once and not inlined, the condition would be a non-builtin `MenaiIRCall`, and we'd conservatively leave the `if` alone. That's correct \u2014 we can't know the return type of an arbitrary user function.\n\nSo the real question is: are there any **builtin** calls that return booleans but aren't predicates or `boolean-not`? Let me check:",
